<br>
The problem with class balancing is really when are classes balanced? There are 2 possibilities:<br>
<br>
1.) All classes are equal - Now that would be boring. If all classes could do the same things, there would be no sense in having different classes. But we have to agree that they would be 100% balanced :-)<br>
<br>
2.) The classes have strengths and weaknesses but are overall possible to achive the same things. - This is what EQ (and all other games) *TRY* to achive. But the more classes you have, the more complicated it is. Imagine you have 3 classes. One (warrior) has strong AC and dishes out medium damage, Two (wizard) has strong damage, but low AC and third (cleric) has strong heals and AC, but no damage. That would work pretty well. But put in a fourth, fifth and so on... it gets more complicated.<br>
<br>
This is the crux with classes. As soon as one clast is &quot;the best&quot; in one line, the other classes can (and will) complain. But basically there are too few &quot;key elements&quot;, meaning some classes can't be the &quot;best&quot; in a field needed. I would say there is healing (cleric), tanking (warrior), damage (rogue/wizard) and maybe crowd control (enchanter). But where is the mage (pet?), shaman (buffs/slow?) or ranger (ehm...)? Verant TRIES to make every class special and to improve their uses. But it really is not easy, even for them having almost 3 years of experience.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Verant can't/won't guarantee that a GM is present on Legends 100% of the time<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually they do. They hired additional GM's to be able to cover Legends 24/7. Although I don't know what exactly that means. I would assume they have about 2 GM's during prime time and one during off-times (with the help of floating GM's). But there shouldn't be a &quot;no GM day&quot; as with other servers. In addition, there will be no volunteer Guides on Legends. They don't want people to get hold of a CS representative who can't help. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> However, I do think that ALL live servers should have 3-6 GMs per, each on 4-8 hour shifts. EverQuest runs 24/7... the GM staff should as well.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree that it would be nice, but I don't know if it would be doable. I don't have the numbers to evaluate if it would still pay off or not, but I guess it will stay a dream. On the other hand, by your own words (and I agree), how often does one really need a GM? I can imagine that if ALL people would only call a GM if the request is valid (as within the guidelines they give for valid petition reasons) it would work.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Re: EQ-killers... SWG won't kill EQ, imo. Star Wars is a bit too narrow in its scope of popularity, as compared to fantasy in general. Star Wars will appeal to Star Wars fans... nobody else, really.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
