<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It's just that Mythic's class balancing has to take PvP into account FAR more than Verant's does.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
EQ was (and probably always will be) a PvE game. The PvP servers suffer a lot from that, as some features of the engine are not built with having PvP in mind (charming, pets, dots etc.). However, IMHO the number of servers and population show that the vast majority of EQ players just plain don't want to do PvP. The fear of getting your fun ruined by some PKillers is way too high.<br>
<br>
Out of that I was amazed when Mythic made PvP a core element of DAoC. I never said &quot;they will fail because of that&quot;, but I knew that the high end game of DAoC would not be what I wanted to do...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Hunters in DAoC were broken so badly that they could 1-shot kill people in PvP. That's more of a problem, when 95% of your high level content *is* PvP. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The funny thing is, that Mythic explained on and on that character building in DAoC is completely different to EQ as it allows more variety. The problem is, that the majority of players will take the path that will result in the most powerfull character. Here and there we hear the question of a new player asking &quot;What is the best class in EQ&quot;? Amazingly, for EQ there is no real answer, but it seems like for DAoC there is (or was). <br>
<br>
The different paths lead into players talking about &quot;templates&quot;. And they advised which skills to take and which not. And if Skill A is 100% effective, while Skil B is only 95% effective, People will Choose A, no matter what (or let's say most will).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The root problem here really is (imo) that Verant's design made it so that if you have enough warriors, enchanters, clerics, you don't really need anything else.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think this is a negative side effect of &quot;complete healing&quot;. The question is, how do I make an encounter more interesting/dangerous? The AI itself is very limited, so it has to be done over damage (through spells or attacks by the MoB) or longer fights (through high HP's, AC, MR and so on). That puts casters in a bad position. If a MoB can CHeal himself, sooner or later the casters are OOM and all their damage is gone. The melee, however, can still fight and continue to make damage. <br>
<br>
Complete Heal pushed the capabilities of warriors with a cleric in his group up (since these warriors now could fight longer), so they had to up the MoBs as well, making the gap between casters and melee even higher.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The larger problem is the players. It's PLAYERS who reinforce the garbage about &quot;Paladins suck&quot;, &quot;Rangers can't tank&quot;, &quot;Druids are useless in groups&quot;, and similar tripe. Until player attitudes change on a large scale, the perceived imbalances will always exist, as will the animosity towards people playing a certain class, regardless of their skill.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That is so true I don't even know what to say. To break this &quot;triumvirate&quot; (cleric, enchanter, warrior) is very hard, as it is deep in the heads of the people. IMHO there is only one solution: <br>
<br>
****Attention, the following statement is a personal Opinion of Ellegon. Disagree as much as you like, but don't flame me <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  **********<br>
<br>
Get rid of &quot;masters&quot;, give multiple classes options. For example: Give Druids a complete heal at higher mana costs than a cleric.<br>
<br>
What would that mean? It means that a raid without clerics could still work, but not as easy as with clerics. But a druid would suddenly be an alternative to the cleric.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, give the cleric a new spell (e.g. Holy Smite) that does some high damage, but at higher costs than a wizard.<br>
<br>
Of course such changes would start in an outcry by the people, but it would close the gap between the classes a bit. For example: I was in ToV quite a few times already. What was my purpose as a Druid? Circle spells (resists) and backup healing. The circles are nice, but with the new SoL spell it's one cast and then the buff is on for 2.5 hours. Now, backup healing.. at level 53 I have Superior Healing. That means, if I cast it on a full buffed warrior, I heal him for about one fourth of a bubble of life. You call that backup healing? I call it a joke. I can heal the cleric itself or an enchanter, but if the cleric goes down, so goes the melee.<br>
<br>
But then, it's easy for me to come up with such ideas and not having to work them out hehe...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It'd be a bad idea to put in writing a guarantee that GM assistance will be available 24/7, otherwise if a GM wasn't available, it'd open up Verant to being sued for a breach of contract. Trust me, *someone* would do it. =)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First, I agree that some would :-)) Second, the wording is a bit vague in that statement by Verant. It says &quot;While you may not see a GM at every log in, with dynamic content ongoing throughout each day, you are sure to be caught up in the weave of stories and events.&quot; Does that mean there is not necessarily a GM online, or just not visible? I agree that it wouldn't be wise to guarantee it, but somehow I belive the server is set up to have 24/7 coverage (maybe with exceptions for breaks etc.). In the end, we can't proof it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> GM hours are designed such that people have a very difficult time getting a hold of them, as most GM hours are something like 10AM PST-6PM PST.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually the GM hours are 2 pm PST to 11 pm PST (which is 5 pm EST to 2 am EST). That looks like decent hours (at least for the americans :-). Interestingly enough, the GM hours on Antonius Bayle are during European Prime Time (meaning VERY early for poor Drembo). But then GM's are often invis or, in the case of a real good GM, helping on other servers as well.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Incidentally, has Verant ever actually said there *would* be an EQ2, and that it was currently in dev? Not doubting you, El, just don't recall hearing anything save for the odd off-hand comment during interviews.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, nothing official, just rumours. I can't even say that I have &quot;sources&quot; because I don't. Or if I'd had, I wouldn't say it :-) But by putting a few things together that I heard here and there, then pressing COMBINE I wouldn't be surprised if it is announced sooner or later :-)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> *snicker* Shadowbane's &quot;booth&quot; at E3 last year was terribly entertaining. It was a few rocks, a small fake pool/fountain, and two 20&quot; monitors stuffed waaaaay in the back of it, showing choppy, half-completed &quot;gameplay&quot;. Heck, they didn't even have booth babes!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No booth babe beats Firiona Vie <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> DAoC is EQ's only real, solid competitor at this point. Mythic had 100,000+ buy the game in the first couple weeks it was out. Even if only 75,000 or so are still playing, that still makes it (more or less) the second most successful MMORPG in the North American Market (I'm not even TOUCHING Lineage. =). Mythic/DAoC have their respective problems, but from everything I've heard about it, it *is* a good game, if you enjoy RvR. They're being a bit heavy with the nerf stick, by the sounds of it, but Verant's done no less or worse, when you get right down to it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Mythic has a hard time and an easy time at the same time. On one hand, it is easy to get &quot;bored&quot; EQ players towards a new game by making promises and create excpectations. With some good PR you can get a lot of players pretty fast. That's why I always told that only the future will show how good DAoC will hold. And that brings us the the hard time: Most of the DAoC players compare DAoC with EverQuest. So whatever is different is rated as &quot;better&quot; or &quot;worse&quot;. If there are more &quot;better&quot; parts people will stay, if there are more &quot;worse&quot; parts, they will go back (or search another game). With PvP being a core item in DAoC and my assumption that the majority of players don't like PvP (based on population numbers of the EQ servers) I would say that more and more players will reach the high level game and then quit.<br>
<br>
Of course that is pessimistic, but I don't see that DAoC will be as successfull as EQ was. But I'm also not sure if ANY game ever can be that successfull again in that genre. EQ was for a long time the only real alternative (next to UO). And probably the lack of PvP was a huge factor in that.<br>
<br>
Does that make DAoC a bad game? No, not at all. But I also wouldn't say it's superior to EQ. It's better in some areas, and worse in others. For me, when I tested it, the bad parts were bigger in numbers so I quit.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Blizzard consistently puts out GREAT stuff, though you have to wait for it. Starcraft was delayed over a year, and enjoyed smashing success. Diablo 2 was in development forever, and also did very, very well. I expect World of Warcraft will be the next big success in the MMORPG market, due to Blizzard's huge pull in the gaming industry. Everything they've put out since 1995 has been pure gold. WoW, hopefully, will be the same. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I kinda disagree here. Starcraft was a GREAT game and still is a lot of fun to play. D2 on the other side was a huge disappointment for me. Of course I bought it, as I trusted Blizzard, but they took away the &quot;fun&quot; of Diablo. <br>
<br>
For me, Diablo was THE game before EQ. I could start a game, kill a few monsters and have some fast fun. I had a few difficulty levels (church, catacombs, cave, hell) with 3 major difficulty levels (ehm...easy, medium, hell?). The 3 races were straightforward and more or less balanced (although the sorceror just rocked). It was fun in multiplayer as solo'ing.<br>
<br>
In D2 they changed some of these nice features. The storyline was better IMHO, but the &quot;touch&quot; got lost. The casters suddenly had to decide what path to take, which brought the fear of being screwed later. I couldn't get better in an area except for leveling and putting points into the skills. In Diablo I just spent some time in the levels, collecting books, and improving my spells with that.<br>
<br>
Also the &quot;Boss types&quot; in D2 were mostly way too powerfull. What I did (and others from what I heard) was to run in, hit the Boss a few times and die. Then run there again, pick up your equipment (only one click needed luckily) and hit on the Boss a few times. Rinse and Repeat.<br>
<br>
Another &quot;bad thing&quot; (and pardon me for letting this post slip a bit :-)) was the equipment part. On one hand, there was this neat idea of armor sets, meaning you find an &quot;Shield of the Eagle&quot; (example) which has some nice stats. Then, later, you might find the &quot;Boots of the Eagle&quot; and so on. Rumour said that if you wear a full set it would be even more powerfull. But how can you collect it? The storage space in that box was a joke. The only chance was to create mule chars and store it on there. Sad as it would have been fun to hunt for your last part (remember hunting for the KSOH in Diablo?).<br>
<br>
Then take the gem concept. Neat plan, but I tried to collect gems and run out of space quickly. And since the lower level gems didn't really add a lot, I had to combine them. To make a long story short: gem hunting wasn't worth it IMHO.<br>
<br>
Of course that is my personal opinion, but I think fewer would have been better in D2 and I never had the fun with it I had with Diablo. :-)<br>
<br>
Anyway, I drifted off a bit. Sorry for that :-)<br>
